    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1047369,
      "reputation" : 423,
      "user_id" : 1052103,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 40,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a210658bf52726f172121b8f4f629e10?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "VincentH",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1052103/vincenth"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 18,
    "last_activity_date" : 1752526922,
    "last_edit_date" : 1752526922,
    "creation_date" : 1701787252,
    "answer_id" : 77607068,
    "question_id" : 7642456,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I could not find the option &quot;Add Framework Support&quot; at all in newer versions of IntelliJ.</p>\n<p>Somehow, I figured out by clicking on the project, then pressing <kbd>Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>Shift</kbd> + <kbd>A</kbd> (Windows) or <kbd>Command</kbd> + <kbd>Shift</kbd> + <kbd>A</kbd> (MacOS), a dialog pops up.</p>\n<p>Start typing &quot;Add Framework Support&quot; and the option will appear in a list. Click that option then you can add Maven support.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 19482358,
      "reputation" : 1,
      "user_id" : 14252370,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a-/AOh14Gi1hbVmcLvzBzypujxJg4NF3xa7dBtiQNwIVCdZcA=k-s256",
      "display_name" : "Bala kumar",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/14252370/bala-kumar"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1719491022,
    "creation_date" : 1719491022,
    "answer_id" : 78677630,
    "question_id" : 7642456,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Sometimes, you don't have Add Framework Support option even in search options too. So, here you can add the pom.xml file. After pasting the sample pom.xml file, you will see intelliJ notification in right bottom that 'Do you need to load as Maven project?'. Here, you can give 'Load as Maven'.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 22627540,
      "reputation" : 1095,
      "user_id" : 16805423,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/LA3Jp.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Brentspine",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/16805423/brentspine"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1761701010,
    "last_edit_date" : 1761701010,
    "creation_date" : 1725372942,
    "answer_id" : 78944786,
    "question_id" : 7642456,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>The above answers work well, as long as the &quot;Add Framework Support&quot; option actually shows up in the context window. If that does not happen, as outlined by many in the comments, you can try the following:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><p>Open your IntelliJ settings by clicking <kbd>☰</kbd> &gt; <code>Settings</code> or pressing <kbd>Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>Alt</kbd> + <kbd>S</kbd></p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Click the search icon and search for <code>Add Framework Support</code></p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/xFTewNei.png\" alt=\"Step 2 preview1\" /></p>\n<ol start=\"3\">\n<li><p>Right click on the keymap result and then click on <code>Add Keyboard Shortcut</code></p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Assign a non existent shortcut, for this example I will use <kbd>Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>Alt</kbd> + <kbd>Shift</kbd> + <kbd>O</kbd>\n<a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/1RN8ZY3L.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/1RN8ZY3L.png\" alt=\"Keyboard Shortcut\" /></a></p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Press okay and ok and close the settings window</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Click on your Project/Module</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Use your assigned Shortcut and the window should show up</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Select Maven and click 'Ok'</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/oJ3TNfRA.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/oJ3TNfRA.png\" alt=\"Maven Add Framework\" /></a></p>\n"
  } ],
